#1 Resected recurrent sigmoid colon cancer, node-negative
Prior to meeting with Mrs. Walton and her family, I have had the opportunity to review her past medical records, laboratory tests, and imaging studies.  At this time, her CT-scan was from home and per quick evaluation did not appear to have any areas of concern.  I will have formal evaluation performed by our colleagues in Radiology and contact patient back regarding this issue.  In regard to further chemotherapy, I have informed Mrs. Walton that there is no right or wrong answer in this situation and that at times observation is what is elected.  This is what the patient is desiring.  It has been quite some time since her surgery and therefore any benefit from adjuvant therapy would be unknown.  Therefore recommending continued observation which would include laboratory tests every three-months with repeat imaging studies at least yearly.  Did inform her that I would more than likely have a CT-scan obtained every six-months.  She will contact her primary oncologist to have the oncologist manage her care.
#2 Urinary stents
At this time, feel that removing the urinary stents would be appropriate.  I did speak with Urology, and they are recommending that approximately four to six-weeks after removal of the urinary stents, then an EXU be performed to determine if there is any evidence of hydronephrosis.  Would be concerned that she may have a stricture from her past radiation exposure.  Oftentimes this can be asymptomatic.  Did counsel patient regarding this issue, and she will followup with her primary-care provider.  If an EXU is not possible, a CT urogram would be the next recommendation.
#3 Followup
At this time, patient is going to continue being followed by her primary oncologist.  She understands that she certainly can contact us at any time should she have any further questions or concerns.  She has our telephone number to contact us.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: No, not interested in additional information.
PATIENT EDUCATION
Ready to learn, no apparent learning barriers were identified; learning preferences include listening.  Explained diagnosis and treatment plan; patient expressed understanding of the content.

